Different options that help improve prim: Different options that help improve priming your extrusion and adhesion to the build plate. Skirt is a line printed around the model, but not connected to the model. Brim adds a single layer flat area around the base of your model to prevent warping. Raft adds a thick grid with a roof below the model.
Distance from the top/bottom of the supp: Distance from the top or bottom of the support structure to the print. This gap provides clearance to remove the supports after the model is printed. This value is rounded up to a multiple of the layer height.
Distance of the ooze shield from the pri: Distance of the ooze shield from the print, in the X and Y direction.

Multiple skirt lines help to prime your: Multiple skirt lines help prime your extrusion better for small models. Setting this to 0 will disable the skirt.

Print a tower next to the print which se: Print a tower next to the print which serves to prime the material after each nozzle switch.
Prints walls in order of outside to insi: When enabled, prints walls in order of outside to inside. This helps improve dimensional accuracy in X and Y when using a high viscosity plastic like ABS; however it can decrease outer surface print quality, especially on overhangs.
Retract the filament when the nozzle is: Retract the filament when the nozzle is moving over a non-printed area.

Settings used for printing with multiple: Settings used for printing with multiple extruders.
Spiralize smooths out the Z move of the: Spiralize smooths out the Z move of the outer edge. This will create a steady Z increase over the whole print. This feature turns a solid model into a single walled print with a solid bottom. This feature should only be enabled when each layer only contains a single part.
The amount of retraction when switching: The amount of retraction when switching nozzles. If set as 0, no retraction at all. This should generally be the same as the length of the heat zone.
The camera hasn't been calibrated yet. P: The camera hasn't been calibrated yet. Please go through Camera Calibration on the Touchscreen first.
The default temperature used for printin: The default temperature used for printing. This should be the "base" temperature of a material. All other print temperatures should use offsets based on this value
The height difference when performing a: The height difference when performing a Z Hop.
The height of each layer in mm. Higher v: The height of each layer in mm. Higher values produce faster prints in lower resolution, lower values produce slower prints in higher resolution.
The height of the initial layer in mm. A: The height of the initial layer in mm. A thicker initial layer makes adhesion to the build plate easier.
The height of the initial layer in mm. A thicker initial layer makes adhesion to the heated bed easier.
The inner diameter of the nozzle. Change: The inner diameter of the nozzle. Change this setting when using a non-standard nozzle size.
The length of material retracted during: The length of material retracted during a retraction move.
The maximum angle a part in the ooze shi: The maximum angle of a part in the ooze shield will have. If set as 0, it will be vertical, and 90 being horizontal. A smaller angle leads to less failed ooze shields, but more material.
The minimum angle of overhangs for which: The minimum angle of overhangs for which support is added. At a value of 0° all overhangs are supported, 90° will not provide any support.
The number of lines used for a brim. Mor: The number of lines used for a brim. More brim lines enhance adhesion to the build plate, but also reduces the effective print area.
The number of lines used for a brim. More brim lines enhance adhesion to the build plate, but also reduces the effective print area.
The pattern of the infill material of th: The pattern of the infill material of the print. The line and zig zag infill swap direction on alternate layers, reducing material cost. The grid, triangle, tri-hexagon, cubic, octet, quarter cubic, cross and concentric patterns are fully printed every layer. Gyroid, cubic, quarter cubic and octet infill change with every layer to provide a more equal distribution of strength over each direction.
The pattern of the support structures of: The pattern of the support structures of the print. The different options available result in sturdy or easy to remove support.
The speed at which all inner walls are p: The speed at which all inner walls are printed. Printing the inner wall faster than the outer wall will reduce printing time. It works well to set this in between the outer wall speed and the infill speed.
The speed at which infill is printed.
The speed at which printing happens.
The speed at which the filament is retra: The speed at which the filament is retracted and primed during a retraction move.
The speed at which the filament is retracted. A higher retraction speed works better, but a very high retraction speed can lead to filament grinding.
The speed at which the outermost walls a: The speed at which the outermost walls are printed. Printing the outer wall at a lower speed improves the final skin quality. However, having a large difference between the inner wall speed and the outer wall speed will affect quality in a negative way.
The speed at which the print cooling fan: The speed at which the print cooling fans spin.
The speed at which top/bottom layers are: The speed at which top or bottom layers are printed.
The speed at which travel moves are made: The speed at which travel moves are made.
The speed of printing for the initial la: The speed of printing for the initial layer. A lower value is advised to improve adhesion to the build plate.
The speed of travel moves in the initial: The speed of travel moves in the initial layer. A lower value is advised to prevent pulling previously printed parts away from the build plate. The value of this setting can automatically be calculated from the ratio between the Travel Speed and the Print Speed.

The speed of travel moves in the initial layer. A lower value is advised to prevent pulling previously printed parts away from the heated bed. The value of this setting can automatically be calculated from the ratio between the Travel Speed and the Print Speed.
The temperature used for printing the fi: The nozzle temperature used for printing the first layer. Set at 0 to disable special handling of the initial layer.
The nozzle temperature used for printing.
The temperature used for the build plate: The temperature used for the build plate at the first layer.
The temperature used for the build plate. If this is 0, the bed temperature will not be adjusted.
The temperature used for the heated buil: The temperature used for the heated build plate at the first layer. If this is 0, the build plate is left unheated during the first layer.
The temperature used for the heated build plate. If this is 0, the build plate is left unheated during the first layer.
The thickness of the bottom layers in th: The thickness of the bottom layers in the print. This value divided by the layer height defines the number of bottom layers.
The thickness of the bottom layers of th: The thickness of the bottom layers of the print. This value divided by the layer height defines the number of bottom layers.
The thickness of the top layers in the p: The thickness of the top layers in the print. This value divided by the layer height defines the number of top layers.
The thickness of the top layers of the p: The thickness of the top layers of the print. This value divided by the layer height defines the number of top layers.
The thickness of the walls in the horizo: The thickness of the walls in the horizontal direction. This value divided by the wall line width defines the number of walls.
Treat the model as a surface only, a vol: Treat the model as a surface only, a volume, or volumes with loose surfaces. The Normal print mode only prints enclosed volumes. The Surface mode prints a single wall tracing the mesh surface with no infill and no top/bottom skin.

1. Place a piece of paper or wood sheet on the platform.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_3: 3. Go to <1>Laser G-code Generator</1> > <3>Camera Capture</3>. Click <5>Add Background</5>.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_4: 4. Engrave a square to locate your material.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_4_1: Set the <1>Side Length</1> and <3>Laser Power</3> of the square. The square should be larger than the material that will be engraved. Click <5>Engrave Square</5>.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_4_2: After the square is engraved, place the material inside the square and take a photo. The four corners of the square must be in the photo. Also, to achieve the best result, try to keep the camera and the build plate parallel.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_4_3: Send the photo to your computer.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_4_4: Click <1>Next</1>. Click <3>Upload</3> to upload the photo. Move the four corners of the dashed box to overlap the four corners of the engraved square.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_4_5: Click <1>Extract</1> and then <3>Complete</3>. Now the printer knows where your material is on the platform.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_5: 5. Add the image or text you need to engrave on the background and adjust the settings.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_6: 6. Click <1>Generate G-code</1> and then <3>Load G-code to Workspace</3>.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_7: 7. Set the work origin only on the Z direction again so that the printer can engrave on the surface of the material. Click <1>Z</1> > <3>Zero Out Temporary Z Axis</3> to save the new origin.
key-Laser/CamaeraCaptureDescription_7_1: Note: If you use a USB flash drive for your project, please make sure you set the work origin in the software instead of on the touchscreen.

key-Workspace/Fine-tuneWorkOriginWidget/: <0>Setting Work Origin</0> is finding the best place for the engraved image in the X and Y directions and determining the Z-axis distance between the platform and the laser module to acquire the smallest laser dot on the material for the best engraved result. For the 200mW Laser Module, the Z Offset can be set by judging the size of the laser dot by eyes. However, for the 1600mW Laser Module, this method is less accurate as the laser dot is too strong and less interpretable. To set the Z Offset more accurately, you should move the module to the position that is close to the optimal Z Offset (Offset A). The software will test the results from a few positions next to Offset A on the same material. The best result determines the best Z Offset.

Click <1></1>to start laser cutting. Choose the position that can cut the material most smoothly or engrave the thinnest line and the software will set the position as Z Offset. In this example, -2.0 should be the Z Offset.

Click <1>Focus</1> and use <3>Jog Pad</3> in the Axes section to move the Laser Cutting Module to the position that is close to the optimal Z Offset (just like how you do with the 200mW Laser Engraving Module).
